				<td class="PanelBodyAlternate"><span class="SmallBoldText">Re: To what extent was Point Blank AE Kiting Nerfed?<a name="71218"/></span><br><span class="SmallText"> Posted: </span><span class="SmallText">Dec 17 04 5:08 PM</span></td>
			</tr><tr>
				<td colspan="2"><span>Hey there, I am about to hit 40 with my Bard and I just started him at Thanksgiving.  Basically, what I have done is tank my way up to 30 and then done fear kiting until 39.  A couple things I had that really helped were an Iksar Ceremonial BP and a pair of Aged Snake Whips (now nerfed to requiring lvl 60).  The straight tanking means that i've kept my defense up the whole time and I don't feel like i've leveled all that slowly.
<br />

<br />
1-4 in newbie zone
<br />

<br />
5-22 in Paludal twisting haste, heal, and eventually slow/snare and just straight tanking the mobs.
<br />

<br />
22-30 in LoIO at the sarnak fort on the platform pulling solo and straight tanking while twisting haste, heal, and slow/snare.  The Heal and Iksar BP kept up with the damage no problem.  As long as I was all the way back on the platform I never had any adds and very little time between my pulls.  Eventually, I stopped worrying so much about getting singles so I could practice mezzing and charming when I have more than 1.  A lot of people say there is an xp penalty in LoIO, but I don't think there is since I was getting about a level in 45 mins to 1 hr at the beginning and 1hr to 1.5hr at the end.
<br />

<br />
30-39 I fought in the Overthere fear kiting.  I would pull the mobs up near the FM zone (just to the right of it if you're looking out from the zone in).  Eventually, you will figure out one spot where mobs will run parallel to the zone wall to minimize adds.  Also, if you get an add, the next time you hit that fear...the add will run off and you can just yo-yo the add until you finish the mob you're fighting.  Here, I was twisting Haste, Snare, and Fear...it's better to let fear or haste drop than Snare/slow if the mob resists the snare song at some point.  Around 36, I moved over near the Skyfire zone since the mobs are slightly higher level in that area.  At that point, pull to the zone wall to the left of the skyfire zone if you are facing out from it.  There are never any adds over there and the mob will run along the zone wall.  At one point, it will look like the mob is going close enough to an NPC that you might worry you will hit her with the fear...but the mob keeps far enough away that you don't have anything to worry about.
<br />

<br />
39+ heading to DL to try that area out.  Will probably finally try to learn swarm kiting and am practicing chant kiting on mobs near the back end of Karnor's castle.
<br />

<br />
Somewhere in the mid 30s there, I went to the City of Mist and grouped for 3/4 of one level.  It is a good spot to make sure you know how to play a bard in a group.  That experience made me realize I will need a lot more practice to be able to group effectively and plan out when to play which songs. (mana, heal, haste, slow/snare, mezzes, etc)  I would definitely suggest fitting in grouping since that experience had me overwhelmed with a crash test of how to group with a bard.
<br />

<br />
Well, that's all I can help with...hopefully i'm not making a fool of myself to the more experienced bards here <img src="/skins/default/images/emotions/emotion-4.gif" border="0" alt="Tongue out" hspace="2" />
<br />

<br />
Hope this newb bard's experiences will help you out a bit.</span></td>
